A Remarkable Shadow
\layout Standard

The numerical evaluation of sums requires a certain amount of cross-checking
 so as to catch errors.
 A particularly curious sum to evaluate is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\eta_{N}(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-\frac{s}{N}\;\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}\left(\frac{2n+1}{2N}\right)^{s}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 which does no permutation at all.
 That is, one effectively has 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{N}(s)=\zeta_{N;p,p}(s)$
\end_inset 

 for any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset 

.
 The limiting integral is trivial to calculate, since 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{p,p}(x)=x$
\end_inset 

, and so 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{N\to\infty}\eta_{N}(s)=\frac{2s}{s^{2}-1}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Thus, this sum shouldn't be interesting, except as a calibration of sorts.
 
\layout Standard

But that is false.
 A review of the figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:A-Shadow-of}

\end_inset 

 shows that this simple stair-step sum retains traces of the locations of
 the non-trivial Riemann zeros!
\layout Standard


