\layout Standard

The presence of this shadow is not hard to explain.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
Z_{N}(s)=\sum_{n=1}^{N}\frac{1}{n^{s}}\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Then it is clear that, for large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{N}(s)$
\end_inset 

will approximate the Riemann zeta function: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\lim_{N\to\infty}Z_{N}(s)=\zeta(s)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 at least for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s>1$
\end_inset 

, where the sum is convergent.
 With some simple manipulations, one may rewrite the numeric sum as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{n=0}^{N-1}\left(\frac{2n+1}{2N}\right)^{s}=\frac{1}{(2N)^{s}}\left[Z_{2N-1}(-s)-2^{s}Z_{N-1}(-s)\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 The fact that the seemingly 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

trivial
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{N}(s)$
\end_inset 

 sum contains this approximation to the zeta would seem to explain the numeric
 features shown in figure 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{cap:A-Shadow-of}

\end_inset 

.
 Furthermore, the presence of the 
\begin_inset Formula $-s$
\end_inset 

 in the arguments appears to explain why the horns are located not far from
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s=-1/2$
\end_inset 

 line.
 
\layout Standard

On the other hand, there is another important lesson to be drawn here: this
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

trivial
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 sum is insufficient to explain the features seen in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{N;p,q}(s)$
\end_inset 

 sums.
 That is, although the numerical evaluation itself is prone to introducing
 the Riemann zeta as an artifact, the strength of this artifact does not
 immediately appear to be dominant enough to account for the entire behavior
 of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{N;p,q}(s)$
\end_inset 

 sums.
 
\layout Section

Conclusions
\layout Standard

Numerical evidence suggests that the permutation-inspired zeta 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\zeta_{p,q}(s)=\lim_{N\to\infty}\zeta_{N;p,q}(s)\]

\end_inset 

 obeys a Riemann hypothesis, in that it's zeros lie in the critical strip,
 and particularly on the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Re s=1/2$
\end_inset 

 line.
 Although the numerical evaluation itself 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

accidentally
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 introduces some zeta-like artifacts, these artifacts do not seem to be
 sufficiently strong to explain the overall structure.
 Alternate means of numerical evaluation, not suffering from this wart,
 are desired, as well as an analysis in terms of traditional holomorphic
 function techniques.
